{"title_page": "27th South African Parliament", "text_new": "{{short description|Current session of South African Parliament}}\n{{Infobox legislative session\n | background_color = Green\n | name                   = 27th South African Parliament\n | image                  = Houses of Parliament (Cape Town).jpg\n | caption                = Houses of Parliament in Cape Town, South Africa\n | body                   = \n | country                = [[South Africa]]\n | state                  = \n | meeting_place          = Cape Town\n | term                   = {{Start date|2019|05|22|df=y}} - Present<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|mm|17|df=y}}\u2013{{End date|YYYY|mm|D|df=y}} -->\n | before                 = \n | after                  = \n | website                = <!-- {{URL|example,com}} -->\n | chamber1               = [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n | membership1            = 400\n | control1               = \n | chamber1_leader1_type  = [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker]]\n | chamber1_leader1       = [[Thandi Modise]] \n | chamber1_leader2_type  = Deputy Speaker\n | chamber1_leader2       = [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] \n | chamber1_leader3_type  = [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n | chamber1_leader3       = [[John Steenhuisen]]\n | chamber2               = [[National Council of Provinces]]\n | membership2            = 90\n | control2               =\n | chamber2_leader1_type  = Chairperson\n | chamber2_leader1       = [[Amos Masondo]]\n | chamber2_leader2_type  = Deputy Chairperson\n | chamber2_leader2       = [[Sylvia Lucas]] \n | chamber2_leader3_type  = Leader of the Opposition\n | chamber2_leader3       = [[Cathlene Labuschagne]]\n}}\n{{South African parliaments}}\nThe '''27th South African Parliament''' is the sixth [[Parliament of South Africa]] to convene since the introduction of non-racial government in [[South Africa]] in 1994. It was elected in the [[2019 South African general election|general election of 8 May 2019]] and consists of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] and the [[National Council of Provinces]]. The National Assembly contains 400 members, while the National Council of Provinces contains 90 members. It was formally opened by President Ramaphosa's State of the Nation Address in a joint sitting on 20 June 2019.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/06/20/more-hell-and-economy-growing-solutions-expected-out-of-cyril-ramaphosa-s-sona Sona 2019: More 'hell' & economy growing solutions expected - EWN]. Retrieved on 24 June 2019.</ref>\n\nMembers of Parliament were sworn in on 22 May 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/parliament-readies-swearing1 WATCH: Newly-elected MPs sworn in]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref> The 27th Parliament first convened on 22 May 2019 to re-elect [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] as President of South Africa.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/cyril-ramaphosa-elected-as-president-of-sa-opposition-wishes-him-well Cyril Ramaphosa elected as president of SA, opposition wishes him well]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFourteen different political parties are represented in this parliament. The majority party in the 26th Parliament, the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) retained its majority, although it was reduced to 230 (57.50%) seats, down from the 249 seats out of 400 (62.25%) it had it in the previous Parliament, while the official opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA) declined from  89 seats (22.25%) in the 26th Parliament to only 84 seats (21%) in the 27th Parliament. Former National Council of Provinces Chairperson [[Thandi Modise]] was elected [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]], while [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] retained his post as Deputy Speaker. Pemmy Majodina was appointed Chief Whip of the ANC caucus.\n\nThe following day, 23 May 2019, the National Council of Provinces reconvened to elect [[Amos Masondo]] as the Chairperson, and [[Sylvia Lucas]] as the Deputy Chairperson. Seiso Mohai remained Chief Whip of the Majority Party.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/sylvia-lucas-deeply-humbled-by-election-as-ncop-deputy-chair-23861150 Sylvia Lucas 'deeply humbled' by election as NCOP deputy chair]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/masondo-elected-ncop-chairperson Masondo elected NCOP chairperson]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Mogoeng Mogoeng.png|180px|thumb|left|New Members of Parliament from fourteen political parties were sworn in by Chief Justice [[Mogoeng Mogoeng]] on 22 May 2019]]\nParliament sits in [[Cape Town]], even though the seat of government is in [[Pretoria]]. Chapter 4 of the [[Constitution of South Africa]] defines the structure of Parliament, the legislative branch of the national government. Parliament consists of two houses, the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] (the lower house), which is directly elected by voters, and the [[National Council of Provinces]] (the upper house), which is elected by each respective [[provincial legislature]].<ref name=\"const\">[[Constitution of South Africa]]</ref>\n\nThe [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] reconvened on 22 May 2019, while the [[National Council of Provinces]] reconvened on the following day, 23 May 2019. According to the Constitution, both Houses of Parliament must be established within fourteen days after the Independent Electoral Commission declared the official election results.<ref>Davis, Gaye. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/02/first-sitting-of-sixth-democratic-parliament-set-for-22-may First sitting of sixth democratic Parliament set for 22 May], Eyewitness News, 2 May 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>Tshabalala, Thabo. [https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/first-sitting-sixth-democratic-parliament-set-22-may/ First sitting of Sixth Democratic Parliament set for 22 May], Jacaranda FM, 2 May 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nChief Justice Mogoeng presided over the swearing-in of MPs and the election of the new Speaker of the National Assembly. Former NCOP Chairperson [[Thandi Modise]] defeated the Democratic Alliance's candidate [[Richard Majola]] by a margin of 250 votes to only 83 votes for Majola. Modise presided over the Deputy Speaker\u2019s election. Incumbent Deputy Speaker [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] of the ANC was re-elected unopposed.<ref>[https://www.parliament.gov.za/na-presiding-officers NA Presiding Officers], Parliament of South Africa. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Chief Justice then presided over the election of the President. Incumbent President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] of the ANC was re-elected unopposed. After the election, Ramaphosa immediately ceased to be a Member of Parliament. Ramaphosa was inaugurated within five days after being elected since the official inauguration took place on 25 May 2019. The inauguration was the first to be held at the [[Loftus Versfeld Stadium]] in [[Pretoria]], and not at the [[Union Buildings]]. The [[Union Buildings]] had been the official venue of the presidential inauguration since the country's first democratically-elected president, [[Nelson Mandela]], took the oath of office in 1994.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/loftus-versfeld-gets-presidential-nod-21417243 Loftus Versfeld gets presidential nod], IOL, 16 April 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/new-presidents-inauguration-to-be-held-at-loftus-in-may-20190413 New president's inauguration to be held at Loftus in May], News24, 13 April 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://rekordeast.co.za/203991/presidential-inauguration-moves-loftus/ Presidential inauguration moves to Loftus]. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nThe first sitting of the National Council of Provinces was held on 23 May 2019. Permanent delegates were sworn in and a Chairperson, Deputy Chairperson, House Chairpersons and Chief Whip were elected.<ref>[https://www.parliament.gov.za/press-releases/road-sixth-democratic-parliament The Road to the Sixth Democratic Parliament], Parliament of South Africa. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ncop-mps-sworn-in-including-former-political-prisoner-kenny-motsamai-20190523 NCOP MPs sworn in, including former political prisoner Kenny Motsamai]. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFormer Mayor of Johannesburg [[Amos Masondo]] was elected Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces, while former Northern Cape Premier [[Sylvia Lucas]] was elected Deputy Chairperson. ANC Chief Whip Seiso Mohai was re-elected.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/masondo-elected-new-ncop-chair-23838556 Masondo elected new #NCOP chair]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\n{{multiple image|perrow=2\n| caption_align=center\n| header = Parliamentary leadership\n\n| image1   = Spotkanie premier Beaty Szyd\u0142o z Thandi Modise (cropped).jpg|width1=121\n| caption1 = NA Speaker [[Thandi Modise]]<br/>(ANC)\n| alt1     = Thandi Modise\n\n| image2   = Manmohan Singh being presented with an appreciation medal by the Executive Mayor, Mr. Amos Masondo at the inauguration of the permanent exhibition - Gandhi A Prisoner of Conscience, at Johannesburg, South Africa (cropped).jpg|width2=145\n| caption2 = NCOP Chairperson [[Amos Masondo]]<br/>(ANC)\n| alt2     = Amos Masondo\n\n}}\nThe African National Congress announced its parliamentary leadership on 20 May 2019. The Democratic Alliance announced the following day that the Parliamentary Leader of the Democratic Alliance, [[Mmusi Maimane]], and Opposition Chief Whip in the National Assembly, [[John Steenhuisen]], would both retain their respective posts. Both were elected to full five-year terms on 30 May 2019 as the DA held parliamentary caucus leadership elections.<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-20-meet-the-ancs-new-team-for-parliament Meet the ANC\u2019s new team for Parliament]. Retrieved on 20 May 2019.</ref> [[Mmusi Maimane]] resigned from Parliament on 24 October 2019. [[John Steenhuisen]] was appointed as his successor with [[Natasha Mazzone]] as the new Chief Whip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-mmusi-maimane-resigns-from-da-20191024|title=Mmusi Maimane resigns from DA and Parliament|date=2019-10-24|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/developing-da-in-crisis-crisis-meetings-in-ct-jhb-to-determine-partys-future-20191024|title=DEVELOPING {{!}} DA in crisis: John Steenhuisen says he's no longer chief whip|date=2019-10-24|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2019, embattled outgoing Minister of Environmental Affairs [[Nomvula Mokonyane]] announced her withdrawal from the ANC parliamentary list, citing family reasons. Mokonyane was initially announced by the ANC as the incoming Chairperson of Committees.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/nomvula-mokonyane-withdraws-anc-mp Nomvula Mokonyane withdraws as ANC MP]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/news-update/2133732/mokonyane-wont-be-taking-up-her-position-as-mp-due-to-family-responsibilities/ Mokonyane won\u2019t be taking up her position as MP due to \u2018family responsibilities\u2019]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref> On 27 June 2019, current parliamentary Chairperson of Committees, [[Cedric Frolick]], was re-elected to his position, despite the official opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] nominating one of its MPs, [[Annelie Lotriet]], for the post. Other elected presiding officers include Grace Boroto and Madala Ntombela.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-06-27-ancs-cedric-frolick-elected-as-parliament-house-chair-but-not-without-drama/ ANC's Cedric Frolick elected as parliament house chair - but not without drama]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/frolick-elected-parliaments-chair-chairs Frolick elected Parliament\u2019s chair of chairs]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/anc-mp-linked-to-bosasa-scandal-elected-national-assembly-house-chair-27767238 ANC MP linked to Bosasa scandal elected National Assembly House chair]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the parliamentary committees elected controversial former Zuma-era cabinet ministers as committee chairpersons. The Democratic Alliance opposed each of the chairpersons in the committee elections. The newly-elected committee chairpersons include [[Faith Muthambi]], [[Sfiso Buthelezi]], [[Tina Joemat-Pettersson]] and [[Bongani Bongo]]. [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] MP [[Mkhuleko Hlengwa]] was elected Chairperson of the Standing Committee on Public Accounts (SCOPA).<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-01-da-to-oppose-problematic-anc-committee-chairpersons/ DA to oppose 'problematic' ANC committee chairpersons]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-07-02-anc-pushes-through-controversial-committee-chairpersons ANC pushes through controversial committee chairpersons]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ifps-mkhuleko-hlengwa-set-to-become-scopa-chair-20190621 IFP's Mkhuleko Hlengwa set to become Scopa chair]. Retrieved on 23 July 2019.</ref>\n===National Assembly===\n*[[President of South Africa|President]] - [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] \n*[[Deputy President of South Africa|Deputy President]] - [[David Mabuza]]\n*[[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker]] - [[Thandi Modise]] \n* Deputy Speaker - [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] \n* Chairperson of Committees - [[Cedric Frolick]]\n* Leader of Government Business - [[David Mabuza]]\n* Government Chief Whip - [[Pemmy Majodina]]\n* Deputy Government Chief Whip - [[Doris Dlakude]]\n* [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] - [[John Steenhuisen]]\n* Official Opposition Chief Whip - [[Natasha Mazzone]]\n\n===National Council of the Provinces===\n* Chairperson - [[Amos Masondo]] \n* Deputy Chairperson - [[Sylvia Lucas]] \n* Government Chief Whip - [[Seiso Mohai]] \n* Leader of the Opposition - [[Cathlene Labuschagne]]\n\n==Current composition==\n\n===National Assembly===\n[[File:Diagram of the National Assembly of South Africa.svg|thumb|x200px|right|Composition of the National Assembly in the 27th Parliament]]\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n!colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left\"| Party !! style=\"text-align:center\"| Seats !! %\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African National Congress}} || 230 || 57.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}} || 84 || 21\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Economic Freedom Fighters}} || 44 || 11\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Inkatha Freedom Party}} || 14 || 3.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Freedom Front Plus}} || 10 || 2.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Christian Democratic Party}} || 4 || 1\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|United Democratic Movement}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Transformation Movement}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Good (political party)}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|National Freedom Party}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Independent Congress}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Pan Africanist Congress of Azania}} || 1 || 0.25\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Al Jama-ah}} || 1 || 0.25\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left\"| Total || style=\"text-align:right\"| 400 || 100.00\n|}\n\n===National Council of Provinces===\n[[File:South African National Council of Provinces 2019.svg|thumb|right|x200px|Composition of the National Council of Provinces in the 27th Parliament; a darker shade represents a permanent delegate while a lighter shade represents a special delegate]]\n{{National Council of Provinces}}\n\n==Membership==\n{{See also|1=List of National Assembly members of the 27th Parliament of South Africa|2=List of members of the National Council of Provinces}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n[[Category:South African parliaments]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Current session of South African Parliament}}\n{{Infobox legislative session\n | background_color = Green\n | name                   = 27th South African Parliament\n | image                  = Houses of Parliament (Cape Town).jpg\n | caption                = Houses of Parliament in Cape Town, South Africa\n | body                   = \n | country                = [[South Africa]]\n | state                  = \n | meeting_place          = Cape Town\n | term                   = {{Start date|2019|05|22|df=y}} - Present<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|mm|17|df=y}}\u2013{{End date|YYYY|mm|D|df=y}} -->\n | before                 = \n | after                  = \n | website                = <!-- {{URL|example,com}} -->\n | chamber1               = [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n | membership1            = 400\n | control1               = \n | chamber1_leader1_type  = [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker]]\n | chamber1_leader1       = [[Thandi Modise]] \n | chamber1_leader2_type  = Deputy Speaker\n | chamber1_leader2       = [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] \n | chamber1_leader3_type  = [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n | chamber1_leader3       = [[John Steenhuisen]]\n | chamber2               = [[National Council of Provinces]]\n | membership2            = 90\n | control2               =\n | chamber2_leader1_type  = Chairperson\n | chamber2_leader1       = [[Amos Masondo]]\n | chamber2_leader2_type  = Deputy Chairperson\n | chamber2_leader2       = [[Sylvia Lucas]] \n | chamber2_leader3_type  = Leader of the Opposition\n | chamber2_leader3       = [[Cathlene Labuschagne]]\n}}\n{{South African parliaments}}\nThe '''27th South African Parliament''' is the sixth [[Parliament of South Africa]] to convene since the introduction of non-racial government in [[South Africa]] in 1994. It was elected in the [[2019 South African general election|general election of 8 May 2019]] and consists of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] and the [[National Council of Provinces]]. The National Assembly contains 400 members, while the National Council of Provinces contains 90 members. It was formally opened by President Ramaphosa's State of the Nation Address in a joint sitting on 20 June 2019.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/06/20/more-hell-and-economy-growing-solutions-expected-out-of-cyril-ramaphosa-s-sona Sona 2019: More 'hell' & economy growing solutions expected - EWN]. Retrieved on 24 June 2019.</ref>\n\nMembers of Parliament were sworn in on 22 May 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/parliament-readies-swearing1 WATCH: Newly-elected MPs sworn in]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref> The 27th Parliament first convened on 22 May 2019 to re-elect [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] as President of South Africa.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/cyril-ramaphosa-elected-as-president-of-sa-opposition-wishes-him-well Cyril Ramaphosa elected as president of SA, opposition wishes him well]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFourteen different political parties are represented in this parliament. The majority party in the 26th Parliament, the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) retained its majority, although it was reduced to 230 (57.50%) seats, down from the 249 seats out of 400 (62.25%) it had it in the previous Parliament, while the official opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA) declined from  89 seats (22.25%) in the 26th Parliament to only 84 seats (21%) in the 27th Parliament. Former National Council of Provinces Chairperson [[Thandi Modise]] was elected [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]], while [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] retained his post as Deputy Speaker. Pemmy Majodina was appointed Chief Whip of the ANC caucus.\n\nThe following day, 23 May 2019, the National Council of Provinces reconvened to elect [[Amos Masondo]] as the Chairperson, and [[Sylvia Lucas]] as the Deputy Chairperson. Seiso Mohai remained Chief Whip of the Majority Party.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/sylvia-lucas-deeply-humbled-by-election-as-ncop-deputy-chair-23861150 Sylvia Lucas 'deeply humbled' by election as NCOP deputy chair]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/masondo-elected-ncop-chairperson Masondo elected NCOP chairperson]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Mogoeng Mogoeng.png|180px|thumb|left|New Members of Parliament from fourteen political parties were sworn in by Chief Justice [[Mogoeng Mogoeng]] on 22 May 2019]]\nParliament sits in [[Cape Town]], even though the seat of government is in [[Pretoria]]. Chapter 4 of the [[Constitution of South Africa]] defines the structure of Parliament, the legislative branch of the national government. Parliament consists of two houses, the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] (the lower house), which is directly elected by voters, and the [[National Council of Provinces]] (the upper house), which is elected by each respective [[provincial legislature]].<ref name=\"const\">[[Constitution of South Africa]]</ref>\n\nThe [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] reconvened on 22 May 2019, while the [[National Council of Provinces]] reconvened on the following day, 23 May 2019. According to the Constitution, both Houses of Parliament must be established within fourteen days after the Independent Electoral Commission declared the official election results.<ref>Davis, Gaye. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/02/first-sitting-of-sixth-democratic-parliament-set-for-22-may First sitting of sixth democratic Parliament set for 22 May], Eyewitness News, 2 May 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>Tshabalala, Thabo. [https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/first-sitting-sixth-democratic-parliament-set-22-may/ First sitting of Sixth Democratic Parliament set for 22 May], Jacaranda FM, 2 May 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nChief Justice Mogoeng presided over the swearing-in of MPs and the election of the new Speaker of the National Assembly. Former NCOP Chairperson [[Thandi Modise]] defeated the Democratic Alliance's candidate [[Richard Majola]] by a margin of 250 votes to only 83 votes for Majola. Modise presided over the Deputy Speaker\u2019s election. Incumbent Deputy Speaker [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] of the ANC was re-elected unopposed.<ref>[https://www.parliament.gov.za/na-presiding-officers NA Presiding Officers], Parliament of South Africa. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Chief Justice then presided over the election of the President. Incumbent President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] of the ANC was re-elected unopposed. After the election, Ramaphosa immediately ceased to be a Member of Parliament. Ramaphosa was inaugurated within five days after being elected since the official inauguration took place on 25 May 2019. The inauguration was the first to be held at the [[Loftus Versfeld Stadium]] in [[Pretoria]], and not at the [[Union Buildings]]. The [[Union Buildings]] had been the official venue of the presidential inauguration since the country's first democratically-elected president, [[Nelson Mandela]], took the oath of office in 1994.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/loftus-versfeld-gets-presidential-nod-21417243 Loftus Versfeld gets presidential nod], IOL, 16 April 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/new-presidents-inauguration-to-be-held-at-loftus-in-may-20190413 New president's inauguration to be held at Loftus in May], News24, 13 April 2019. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://rekordeast.co.za/203991/presidential-inauguration-moves-loftus/ Presidential inauguration moves to Loftus]. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref>\n\nThe first sitting of the National Council of Provinces was held on 23 May 2019. Permanent delegates were sworn in and a Chairperson, Deputy Chairperson, House Chairpersons and Chief Whip were elected.<ref>[https://www.parliament.gov.za/press-releases/road-sixth-democratic-parliament The Road to the Sixth Democratic Parliament], Parliament of South Africa. Retrieved on 2 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ncop-mps-sworn-in-including-former-political-prisoner-kenny-motsamai-20190523 NCOP MPs sworn in, including former political prisoner Kenny Motsamai]. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFormer Mayor of Johannesburg [[Amos Masondo]] was elected Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces, while former Northern Cape Premier [[Sylvia Lucas]] was elected Deputy Chairperson. ANC Chief Whip Seiso Mohai was re-elected.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/masondo-elected-new-ncop-chair-23838556 Masondo elected new #NCOP chair]. Retrieved on 24 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\n{{multiple image|perrow=2\n| caption_align=center\n| header = Parliamentary leadership\n\n| image1   = Spotkanie premier Beaty Szyd\u0142o z Thandi Modise (cropped).jpg|width1=121\n| caption1 = NA Speaker [[Thandi Modise]]<br/>(ANC)\n| alt1     = Thandi Modise\n\n| image2   = Manmohan Singh being presented with an appreciation medal by the Executive Mayor, Mr. Amos Masondo at the inauguration of the permanent exhibition - Gandhi A Prisoner of Conscience, at Johannesburg, South Africa (cropped).jpg|width2=145\n| caption2 = NCOP Chairperson [[Amos Masondo]]<br/>(ANC)\n| alt2     = Amos Masondo\n\n}}\nThe African National Congress announced its parliamentary leadership on 20 May 2019. The Democratic Alliance announced the following day that the Parliamentary Leader of the Democratic Alliance, [[Mmusi Maimane]], and Opposition Chief Whip in the National Assembly, [[John Steenhuisen]], would both retain their respective posts. Both were elected to full five-year terms on 30 May 2019 as the DA held parliamentary caucus leadership elections.<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-20-meet-the-ancs-new-team-for-parliament Meet the ANC\u2019s new team for Parliament]. Retrieved on 20 May 2019.</ref> [[Mmusi Maimane]] resigned from Parliament on 24 October 2019. [[John Steenhuisen]] was appointed as his successor with [[Natasha Mazzone]] as the new Chief Whip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-mmusi-maimane-resigns-from-da-20191024|title=Mmusi Maimane resigns from DA and Parliament|date=2019-10-24|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/developing-da-in-crisis-crisis-meetings-in-ct-jhb-to-determine-partys-future-20191024|title=DEVELOPING {{!}} DA in crisis: John Steenhuisen says he's no longer chief whip|date=2019-10-24|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2019, embattled outgoing Minister of Environmental Affairs [[Nomvula Mokonyane]] announced her withdrawal from the ANC parliamentary list, citing family reasons. Mokonyane was initially announced by the ANC as the incoming Chairperson of Committees.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/nomvula-mokonyane-withdraws-anc-mp Nomvula Mokonyane withdraws as ANC MP]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/news-update/2133732/mokonyane-wont-be-taking-up-her-position-as-mp-due-to-family-responsibilities/ Mokonyane won\u2019t be taking up her position as MP due to \u2018family responsibilities\u2019]. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref> On 27 June 2019, current parliamentary Chairperson of Committees, [[Cedric Frolick]], was re-elected to his position, despite the official opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] nominating one of its MPs, [[Annelie Lotriet]], for the post. Other elected presiding officers include Grace Boroto and Madala Ntombela.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-06-27-ancs-cedric-frolick-elected-as-parliament-house-chair-but-not-without-drama/ ANC's Cedric Frolick elected as parliament house chair - but not without drama]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/frolick-elected-parliaments-chair-chairs Frolick elected Parliament\u2019s chair of chairs]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/anc-mp-linked-to-bosasa-scandal-elected-national-assembly-house-chair-27767238 ANC MP linked to Bosasa scandal elected National Assembly House chair]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the parliamentary committees elected controversial former Zuma-era cabinet ministers as committee chairpersons. The Democratic Alliance opposed each of the chairpersons in the committee elections. The newly-elected committee chairpersons include [[Faith Muthambi]], [[Sfiso Buthelezi]], [[Tina Joemat-Pettersson]] and [[Bongani Bongo]]. [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] MP [[Mkhuleko Hlengwa]] was elected Chairperson of the Standing Committee on Pulic Accounts (SCOPA).<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-01-da-to-oppose-problematic-anc-committee-chairpersons/ DA to oppose 'problematic' ANC committee chairpersons]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-07-02-anc-pushes-through-controversial-committee-chairpersons ANC pushes through controversial committee chairpersons]. Retrieved on 15 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ifps-mkhuleko-hlengwa-set-to-become-scopa-chair-20190621 IFP's Mkhuleko Hlengwa set to become Scopa chair]. Retrieved on 23 July 2019.</ref>\n===National Assembly===\n*[[President of South Africa|President]] - [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] \n*[[Deputy President of South Africa|Deputy President]] - [[David Mabuza]]\n*[[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker]] - [[Thandi Modise]] \n* Deputy Speaker - [[Solomon Lechesa Tsenoli]] \n* Chairperson of Committees - [[Cedric Frolick]]\n* Leader of Government Business - [[David Mabuza]]\n* Government Chief Whip - [[Pemmy Majodina]]\n* Deputy Government Chief Whip - [[Doris Dlakude]]\n* [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] - [[John Steenhuisen]]\n* Official Opposition Chief Whip - [[Natasha Mazzone]]\n\n===National Council of the Provinces===\n* Chairperson - [[Amos Masondo]] \n* Deputy Chairperson - [[Sylvia Lucas]] \n* Government Chief Whip - [[Seiso Mohai]] \n* Leader of the Opposition - [[Cathlene Labuschagne]]\n\n==Current composition==\n\n===National Assembly===\n[[File:Diagram of the National Assembly of South Africa.svg|thumb|x200px|right|Composition of the National Assembly in the 27th Parliament]]\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n!colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left\"| Party !! style=\"text-align:center\"| Seats !! %\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African National Congress}} || 230 || 57.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}} || 84 || 21\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Economic Freedom Fighters}} || 44 || 11\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Inkatha Freedom Party}} || 14 || 3.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Freedom Front Plus}} || 10 || 2.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Christian Democratic Party}} || 4 || 1\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|United Democratic Movement}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Transformation Movement}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Good (political party)}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|National Freedom Party}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name with color|African Independent Congress}} || 2 || 0.5\n|-\n| {{Party name