the Bulls during the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[1997-98 NBA season|season]]. The 10-part miniseries<ref name=\"maxim\">{{cite news |title=ESPN Documentary 'The Last Dance' About Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls, Gets a New Trailer |url=https://www.maxim.com/sports/the-last-dance-michael-jackson-bulls-documentary-2019-12 |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228080305/https://www.maxim.com/sports/the-last-dance-michael-jackson-bulls-documentary-2019-12 |archive-date=December 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> was announced by [[ESPN]] in 2018 with an official trailer released on December 24, 2019.<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite news |last1=Welk |first1=Brian |title='The Last Dance' Trailer: Barack Obama, Justin Timberlake Reflect on Legend of Michael Jordan and '90s Chicago Bulls (Video) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-last-dance-trailer-barack-obama-justin-timberlake-reflect-on-legend-of-michael-jordan-and-90s-chicago-bulls-video/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103131131/https://www.thewrap.com/the-last-dance-trailer-barack-obama-justin-timberlake-reflect-on-legend-of-michael-jordan-and-90s-chicago-bulls-video/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"espntwitter\" />\n\n== Premise ==\nThe series will focus on the [[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season]] and [[Michael Jordan]]'s final season with the Bulls.<ref name=\"espnpressrelease\">{{cite press release |last=Christie |first=Jennifer |date=May 18, 2018 |title=ESPN Films, Netflix Announce Multi-Part Documentary The Last Dance featuring Michael Jordan |url=https://espnpressroom.com/us/press-releases/2018/05/espn-films-and-netflix-announce-multi-part-documentary-the-last-dance-featuring-michael-jordan/ |location=New York, New York |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency= |access-date=January 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121121814/https://espnpressroom.com/us/press-releases/2018/05/espn-films-and-netflix-announce-multi-part-documentary-the-last-dance-featuring-michael-jordan/ |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table| background=8B0000 |overall=5 |title=23 |director=20 |writer=20 |airdate=18 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|19}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|19}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title          = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|3}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|3}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|10}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}     \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|10}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|17}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}     \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|17}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n}}\n\n== Production and release ==\nThe series features both interviews and never-released footage from the 1997-98 NBA season. The series was first announced in May 2018,<ref name=\"espnpressrelease\" /> with the first official trailer being released on December 25, 2018.<ref name=\"complex2018\">{{cite news |last1=Espinosa |first1=Joshua |title=Here's the Thrilling New Trailer for ESPN's Michael Jordan Documentary 'The Last Dance' |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2018/12/michael-jordan-last-dance-documentary-trailer |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227131640/https://www.complex.com/sports/2018/12/michael-jordan-last-dance-documentary-trailer |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"espnfirsttrailer\">{{cite tweet |user=ESPNNBA |number=1077434223689113600 |date=December 25, 2018 |title=Cannot. Wait.}}</ref> The release date was pushed back to June 2020 after another trailer was released in December 2019.<ref name=\"complex2019\">{{cite news |last1=Tigg |first1=FNR |title=Latest Trailer for Michael Jordan Doc 'The Last Dance' Features Barack Obama, Nas and More |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/12/michael-jordan-documentary-the-last-dance-trailer |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225174301/https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/12/michael-jordan-documentary-the-last-dance-trailer |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, because of the impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], ESPN published the final trailer on March 31, 2020 and expedited the premiere to April 19, 2020, releasing the following statement:<ref name=\"NBA.com\">{{cite web |title='The Last Dance' documentary set to air April 19 on ESPN |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/31/last-dance-chicago-bulls-release-date-moved |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |website=[[NBA.com]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131255/https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/31/last-dance-chicago-bulls-release-date-moved |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{Quotation|As society navigates this time without live sports, viewers are still looking to the sports world to escape and enjoy a collective experience. We've heard the calls from fans asking us to move up the release date for this series, and we\u2019re happy to announce that we\u2019ve been able to accelerate the production schedule to do just that. This project celebrates one of the greatest players and dynasties ever, and we hope it can serve as a unifying entertainment experience to fill the role that sports often play in our lives, telling a story that will captivate everyone, not just sports fans.}}\n\nThe series is scheduled to be released weekly from April 19, 2020 to May 17, 2020, with two episodes airing each Sunday.<ref name=\"NBA.com\" /> Outside of the United States, the episodes are set to be released on [[Netflix]] the day after their ESPN airing.<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.espn.com/watch/series/0514c1ad-efd1-4d3a-ad82-41ca579a94a2/30-for-30}}\n* {{IMDb title|8420184}}\n\n{{30 for 30}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Dance (2020 documentary series)}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:30 for 30]]\n[[Category:ESPN Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 sports documentary miniseries}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Last Dance\n| image                = \n| image_upright        = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Television documentary<ref name=\"chicagotribune\">{{cite news |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Phil |title=ESPN offers a peek at their '30 for 30' documentary on Dennis Rodman: 'A much more complex and nuanced picture emerges' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/bulls/ct-bulls-espn-dennis-rodman-20190815-ae3a5lhsafax3fmxrco7pma55y-story.html |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=August 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202073630/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/bulls/ct-bulls-espn-dennis-rodman-20190815-ae3a5lhsafax3fmxrco7pma55y-story.html |archive-date=December 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><br>[[Miniseries]]\n| creator              = \n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| story                = \n| director             = Jason Hehir<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news |last1=Chavez |first1=Chris |title=ESPN's Latest Trailer for 'The Last Dance' Features Michael Jordan, Bulls Legends, President Obama |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/12/24/espn-last-dance-documentary-trailer-michael-jordan-chicago-bulls-1997-1998 |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209112620/https://www.si.com/nba/2019/12/24/espn-last-dance-documentary-trailer-michael-jordan-chicago-bulls-1997-1998 |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| creative_director    = \n| presenter            = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| starring             = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| judges               = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| voices               = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| narrated             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = \n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 10\n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = \n| producer             = [[Michael Tollin]]\n| cinematography       = \n| editor               = \n| camera               = Single-camera\n| runtime              = 60 minutes<ref name=\"nbcsportschicago\">{{cite news |last1=Roumeliotis |first1=Charlie |title='The Last Dance': ESPN to release 10-hour documentary series on Michael Jordan, 1990s Bulls |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/chicago/bulls/last-dance-espn-release-10-hour-documentary-series-michael-jordan-1990s-bulls |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC Sports Chicago]] |date=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n| company              = [[NBA Entertainment]]<br>Mandalay Sports Media<br>Jump23<br>[[ESPN Films]]<br>[[Netflix]]<ref name=\"nbcsportschicago\" />\n| network              = [[ESPN]]\n| picture_format       = \n| released             = {{Start date|2020|6}}<ref name=\"espntwitter\">{{cite tweet |user=ESPN |number=1209463737058562048 |date=December 24, 2019 |title=IT'S HAPPENING #TheLastDance | Coming in June}}</ref>\n| first_aired          = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| related              = ''[[30 for 30]]''\n| website              = https://www.espn.com/watch/series/0514c1ad-efd1-4d3a-ad82-41ca579a94a2/30-for-30-spotlight\n}}\n\n'''''The Last Dance''''' is a 2020 [[Television documentary|sports documentary]] miniseries focusing on the  [[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season|1997\u201398]] [[Chicago Bulls]]. The series will feature film from a crew that had all-access pass to the Bulls during the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[1997-98 NBA season|season]]. The 10-part miniseries<ref name=\"maxim\">{{cite news |title=ESPN Documentary 'The Last Dance' About Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls, Gets a New Trailer |url=https://www.maxim.com/sports/the-last-dance-michael-jackson-bulls-documentary-2019-12 |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228080305/https://www.maxim.com/sports/the-last-dance-michael-jackson-bulls-documentary-2019-12 |archive-date=December 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> was announced by [[ESPN]] in 2018 with an official trailer released on December 24, 2019.<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite news |last1=Welk |first1=Brian |title='The Last Dance' Trailer: Barack Obama, Justin Timberlake Reflect on Legend of Michael Jordan and '90s Chicago Bulls (Video) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-last-dance-trailer-barack-obama-justin-timberlake-reflect-on-legend-of-michael-jordan-and-90s-chicago-bulls-video/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103131131/https://www.thewrap.com/the-last-dance-trailer-barack-obama-justin-timberlake-reflect-on-legend-of-michael-jordan-and-90s-chicago-bulls-video/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"espntwitter\" />\n\n== Premise ==\nThe series will focus on the [[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season]] and [[Michael Jordan]]'s final season with the Bulls.<ref name=\"espnpressrelease\">{{cite press release |last=Christie |first=Jennifer |date=May 18, 2018 |title=ESPN Films, Netflix Announce Multi-Part Documentary The Last Dance featuring Michael Jordan |url=https://espnpressroom.com/us/press-releases/2018/05/espn-films-and-netflix-announce-multi-part-documentary-the-last-dance-featuring-michael-jordan/ |location=New York, New York |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency= |access-date=January 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121121814/https://espnpressroom.com/us/press-releases/2018/05/espn-films-and-netflix-announce-multi-part-documentary-the-last-dance-featuring-michael-jordan/ |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table| background=8B0000 |overall=5 |title=23 |director=20 |writer=20 |airdate=18 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|19}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|19}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title          = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|3}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|3}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|10}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}     \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|10}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|17}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}     \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = \n |DirectedBy      = Jason Hehir\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|17}}<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 8B0000\n |Viewers         = \n}}\n}}\n\n== Production and release ==\nThe series features both interviews and never-released footage from the 1997-98 NBA season. The series was first announced in May 2018,<ref name=\"espnpressrelease\" /> with the first official trailer being released on December 25, 2018.<ref name=\"complex2018\">{{cite news |last1=Espinosa |first1=Joshua |title=Here's the Thrilling New Trailer for ESPN's Michael Jordan Documentary 'The Last Dance' |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2018/12/michael-jordan-last-dance-documentary-trailer |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227131640/https://www.complex.com/sports/2018/12/michael-jordan-last-dance-documentary-trailer |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"espnfirsttrailer\">{{cite tweet |user=ESPNNBA |number=1077434223689113600 |date=December 25, 2018 |title=Cannot. Wait.}}</ref> The release date was pushed back to June 2020 after another trailer was released in December 2019.<ref name=\"complex2019\">{{cite news |last1=Tigg |first1=FNR |title=Latest Trailer for Michael Jordan Doc 'The Last Dance' Features Barack Obama, Nas and More |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/12/michael-jordan-documentary-the-last-dance-trailer |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225174301/https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/12/michael-jordan-documentary-the-last-dance-trailer |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, because of the impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], ESPN published the final trailer on March 31, 2020 and expedited the premiere to April 19, 2020, releasing the following statement:<ref name=\"NBA.com\">{{cite web |title='The Last Dance' documentary set to air April 19 on ESPN |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/31/last-dance-chicago-bulls-release-date-moved |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |website=[[NBA.com]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131255/https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/31/last-dance-chicago-bulls-release-date-moved |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{Quotation|As society navigates this time without live sports, viewers are still looking to the sports world to escape and enjoy a collective experience. We've heard the calls from fans asking us to move up the release date for this series, and we\u2019re happy to announce that we\u2019ve been able to accelerate the production schedule to do just that. This project celebrates one of the greatest players and dynasties ever, and we hope it can serve as a unifying entertainment experience to fill the role that sports often play in our lives, telling a story that will captivate everyone, not just sports fans.}}\n\nThe series is scheduled to be released weekly from April 19, 2020 to May 17, 2020, with two episodes airing each Sunday.<ref name=\"NBA.com\" /> Outside of the United States, the episodes are set to be released on [[Netflix]] the day after their ESPN airing.<ref name=\"NBA.com\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.espn.com/watch/series/0514c1ad-efd1-4d3a-ad82-41ca579a94a2/30-for-30}}\n* {{IMDb title|8420184}}\n\n{{30 for 30}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Dance (2020 documentary series)}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:30 for 30]]\n[[Category:ESPN Films films]]\n", "name_user": "Mazewaxie", "label": "safe", "comment": "American English, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Last_Dance_(2020_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Pod Save America", "text_new": "{{short description|American political podcast}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Podcast\n |show_name     = Pod Save America (Extremely biased)\n |image         = Pod_save_america_logo.jpg\n |caption       = \n |alt           =\n |updates       = Twice weekly\n |runtime       = 41\u201396 minutes\n |country       = United States\n |language      = English\n |presenter     = {{ubl|[[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]]|[[Daniel Pfeiffer]]|[[Jon Lovett]]|[[Tommy Vietor]]}}\n |first_aired   = {{Start date|2017|1}}\n |last_aired    = \n |num_episodes  =\n |audio_format  =\n |website       = {{URL|https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/}}\n |provider      = [[Cadence13]]\n |genre         = Political\n}}\n\n'''''Pod Save America''''' is an American [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] [[political podcast]] produced and distributed by [[Crooked Media]]. The podcast debuted in January 2017 and airs twice weekly, with the Monday edition hosted by former [[Barack Obama]] staffers [[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]], [[Tommy Vietor]], and [[Jon Lovett]], and the Thursday edition by Favreau and [[Daniel Pfeiffer|Dan Pfeiffer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/18/podcasts-trump-presidency-political-left-right-alt-right|title=Pod save America: 12 podcasts to get you through the Trump presidency|first=Craille Maguire|last=Gillies|date=January 18, 2017|publisher=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/20/business/media/rutenberg-trump-opposition-pod-save-america.html|title=Opposition and a Shave: Former Obama Aides Counter Trump|last=Rutenberg|first=Jim|date=March 20, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 22, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/pod-save-america-colbert|title=The Pod Save America Guys Have Some Ideas About What President Obama Should Do Next|last=Willis|first=Jay|date=April 6, 2017|work=GQ|access-date=June 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/crooked-media-fights-trump-pod-save-america-jon-favreau-jon-lovett-tommy-570695|title=Crooked Media Fights Trump with \"Pod Save America\"|date=March 26, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt is the flagship podcast of [[Crooked Media]], a media company founded by Favreau, Vietor, and Lovett.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/01/09/the-keepin-it-1600-guys-launch-crooked-media-to-counter-trump|title=The 'Keepin' It 1600' Guys Launch Crooked Media to Counter Trump|last=Wilstein|first=Matt|date=January 9, 2017|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The show averages more than 3.5 million listeners an episode, and has been downloaded more than 120 million times as of November 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/22/magazine/the-voices-in-blue-americas-head.html?smid=tw-nytimes&smtyp=cur|title=The Voices in Blue America's Head|last=Zengerle|first=Jason|access-date=November 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref> \n\nFour ''Pod Save America'' one-hour [[HBO]] TV specials aired in fall 2018 to cover the [[United States elections, 2018|U.S. midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hbo.com/hbo-news/pod-save-america-podcast-specials|title=- HBO Announces Pod Save America Podcast Specials|website=HBO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pod-save-america-getting-hbo-treatment-election-specials-1083148|title='Pod Save America' Getting HBO Treatment With Election Specials|website=hollywoodreporter.com}}</ref> Crooked Media also films the podcasts and releases them on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKRoXz3hHAu2XL_k3Ef4vJQ/videos|title=Crooked Media|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe podcast debuted in January 2017 as a successor to ''[[Keepin' it 1600]]'', a political podcast produced by [[Bill Simmons]]' [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] and hosted by Favreau, Vietor, Lovett, and Pfeiffer which ran from March to December 2016. ''Pod Save America'' maintained the basic format of its predecessor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/keeping-1600-podcasts-obama-alums-launch-new-show-crooked-media-company-961556|title='Keeping It 1600' Podcast's Obama Alums Launch New Show and 'Crooked Media' Company|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Recode]]'s [[Kara Swisher]], the hosts have stated that, rather than continue the previous podcast, the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President of the United States|President]] of the [[United States]] spurred them to create a progressive media company with a network of podcasts. Their goal is to inform their millions of fans and viewers that trust them as a reliable source.\n\n== Tour ==\nCrooked Media took the podcast on its first live tour, ''Pod Tours America,'' in the fall of 2017. Live shows were recorded and released as podcasts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/08/pod-save-america-announces-nationwide-tour/|title=Pod Save America announces nationwide tour|date=August 16, 2017|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> An international tour, ''Pod Tours the World'', was announced for 2018, with live shows in Stockholm, Oslo, Amsterdam, and London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/97781-pod-save-america-and-lovett-or-leave-it-are-coming-to-london-in-january-heres-how-to-get-tickets/|title=Pod Save America and Lovett or Leave It are coming to London in January, here's how to get tickets|date=December 1, 2017|work=The List|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe podcast typically covers recent news items relating to politics, including the Trump administration, the US government and the Democratic Party, as well as progressive grassroots activism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/19/the-week-in-radio-pod-save-america-the-long-view-podcast|title=The week in radio: Pod Save America; The Long View|last=Sawyer|first=Miranda|date=March 19, 2017|work=The Observer|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nThe show typically features interviews with politicians, activists and journalists, including Obama's last interview as president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/26/pod-save-america-the-podcast-that-won-obamas-last-interview|title=Pod Save America \u2013 the podcast that won Obama's last interview|last=Verdier|first=Hannah|date=January 26, 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other guests have included [[Hillary Clinton]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/hillary-clinton-trump-clear-present-threat-pod-save-america-podcast-interview-a7943726.html|title=Hillary Clinton says Donald Trump 'is a clear and present danger to America'|date=September 12, 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> and senators [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Elizabeth Warren]], [[Cory Booker]], [[Kamala Harris]], and [[Chris Murphy (Connecticut politician)|Chris Murphy]]. They have interviewed several current and former [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 Democratic Presidential candidates]], including Sanders, Booker, Harris, [[Beto O'Rourke]], [[Andrew Yang]], [[Pete Buttigieg]], [[Marianne Williamson]], and [[Amy Klobuchar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/|title=Pod Save America Archives|website=Crooked Media|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>. Guests are often referred to as \"friends of the pod\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/en_ca/article/a3jadk/podcasts-are-becoming-the-lefts-right-wing-talk-radio|title=Podcasts are becoming the left's right-wing talk radio|work=VICE News|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pod Save America (30363).jpg|thumb|Favreau, Vietor, and guest [[Seth Meyers]] at a live taping at [[Radio City Music Hall]]]]\n\n== Reception ==\nThe show averages more than 1.5 million listeners an episode, and had been downloaded more than 120 million times by November 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' described the podcast as \"one of the big breakout hits of the nascent resistance movement\",<ref name=\":1\" /> and \"the left's answer to conservative talk radio... with a shoestring budget and no organizational backing, its hosts seem to have created something that liberals have spent almost two decades, and hundreds of millions of dollars, futilely searching for\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called it \"one of the nation's most popular podcasts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Pod-Save-America-about-to-take-its-next-step-12418780.php|title='Pod Save America' about to take its next step|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> ''[[GQ]]'' called it one of the \"most popular strategies for coping with the looming death of the republic\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/pod-save-america-colbert|title=The 'Pod Save America' Guys Gave Donald Trump His Best, Weirdest Nickname Yet|last=Willis|first=Jay|date=April 6, 2017|work=GQ|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote that the show's hosts \"do something far more rare [than political analysis], which is to make politics entertaining and even fun, without ever downplaying what they see as the threat posed to American democracy by the man elected to defend it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/crooked-media-fights-trump-pod-save-america-jon-favreau-jon-lovett-tommy-570695|title=How the Crooked Media trio is taking on Donald Trump with \"Pod Save America\"|date=March 26, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pod Save the World]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/}}\n\n{{Crooked Media}}\n\n[[Category:2017 podcast debuts]]\n[[Category:Audio podcasts]]\n[[Category:Political podcasts]]\n[[Category:Crooked Media]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political podcast}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Podcast\n |show_name     = Pod Save America\n |image         = Pod_save_america_logo.jpg\n |caption       = \n |alt           =\n |updates       = Twice weekly\n |runtime       = 41\u201396 minutes\n |country       = United States\n |language      = English\n |presenter     = {{ubl|[[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]]|[[Daniel Pfeiffer]]|[[Jon Lovett]]|[[Tommy Vietor]]}}\n |first_aired   = {{Start date|2017|1}}\n |last_aired    = \n |num_episodes  =\n |audio_format  =\n |website       = {{URL|https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/}}\n |provider      = [[Cadence13]]\n |genre         = Political\n}}\n\n'''''Pod Save America''''' is an American [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] [[political podcast]] produced and distributed by [[Crooked Media]]. The podcast debuted in January 2017 and airs twice weekly, with the Monday edition hosted by former [[Barack Obama]] staffers [[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]], [[Tommy Vietor]], and [[Jon Lovett]], and the Thursday edition by Favreau and [[Daniel Pfeiffer|Dan Pfeiffer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/18/podcasts-trump-presidency-political-left-right-alt-right|title=Pod save America: 12 podcasts to get you through the Trump presidency|first=Craille Maguire|last=Gillies|date=January 18, 2017|publisher=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/20/business/media/rutenberg-trump-opposition-pod-save-america.html|title=Opposition and a Shave: Former Obama Aides Counter Trump|last=Rutenberg|first=Jim|date=March 20, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 22, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/pod-save-america-colbert|title=The Pod Save America Guys Have Some Ideas About What President Obama Should Do Next|last=Willis|first=Jay|date=April 6, 2017|work=GQ|access-date=June 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/crooked-media-fights-trump-pod-save-america-jon-favreau-jon-lovett-tommy-570695|title=Crooked Media Fights Trump with \"Pod Save America\"|date=March 26, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt is the flagship podcast of [[Crooked Media]], a media company founded by Favreau, Vietor, and Lovett.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/01/09/the-keepin-it-1600-guys-launch-crooked-media-to-counter-trump|title=The 'Keepin' It 1600' Guys Launch Crooked Media to Counter Trump|last=Wilstein|first=Matt|date=January 9, 2017|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The show averages more than 3.5 million listeners an episode, and has been downloaded more than 120 million times as of November 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/22/magazine/the-voices-in-blue-americas-head.html?smid=tw-nytimes&smtyp=cur|title=The Voices in Blue America's Head|last=Zengerle|first=Jason|access-date=November 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref> \n\nFour ''Pod Save America'' one-hour [[HBO]] TV specials aired in fall 2018 to cover the [[United States elections, 2018|U.S. midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hbo.com/hbo-news/pod-save-america-podcast-specials|title=- HBO Announces Pod Save America Podcast Specials|website=HBO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pod-save-america-getting-hbo-treatment-election-specials-1083148|title='Pod Save America' Getting HBO Treatment With Election Specials|website=hollywoodreporter.com}}</ref> Crooked Media also films the podcasts and releases them on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKRoXz3hHAu2XL_k3Ef4vJQ/videos|title=Crooked Media|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe podcast debuted in January 2017 as a successor to ''[[Keepin' it 1600]]'', a political podcast produced by [[Bill Simmons]]' [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] and hosted by Favreau, Vietor, Lovett, and Pfeiffer which ran from March to December 2016. ''Pod Save America'' maintained the basic format of its predecessor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/keeping-1600-podcasts-obama-alums-launch-new-show-crooked-media-company-961556|title='Keeping It 1600' Podcast's Obama Alums Launch New Show and 'Crooked Media' Company|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Recode]]'s [[Kara Swisher]], the hosts have stated that, rather than continue the previous podcast, the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President of the United States|President]] of the [[United States]] spurred them to create a progressive media company with a network of podcasts. Their goal is to inform their millions of fans and viewers that trust them as a reliable source.\n\n== Tour ==\nCrooked Media took the podcast on its first live tour, ''Pod Tours America,'' in the fall of 2017. Live shows were recorded and released as podcasts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/08/pod-save-america-announces-nationwide-tour/|title=Pod Save America announces nationwide tour|date=August 16, 2017|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> An international tour, ''Pod Tours the World'', was announced for 2018, with live shows in Stockholm, Oslo, Amsterdam, and London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/97781-pod-save-america-and-lovett-or-leave-it-are-coming-to-london-in-january-heres-how-to-get-tickets/|title=Pod Save America and Lovett or Leave It are coming to London in January, here's how to get tickets|date=December 1, 2017|work=The List|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe podcast typically covers recent news items relating to politics, including the Trump administration, the US government and the Democratic Party, as well as progressive grassroots activism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/19/the-week-in-radio-pod-save-america-the-long-view-podcast|title=The week in radio: Pod Save America; The Long View|last=Sawyer|first=Miranda|date=March 19, 2017|work=The Observer|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nThe show typically features interviews with politicians, activists and journalists, including Obama's last interview as president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/26/pod-save-america-the-podcast-that-won-obamas-last-interview|title=Pod Save America \u2013 the podcast that won Obama's last interview|last=Verdier|first=Hannah|date=January 26, 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other guests have included [[Hillary Clinton]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/hillary-clinton-trump-clear-present-threat-pod-save-america-podcast-interview-a7943726.html|title=Hillary Clinton says Donald Trump 'is a clear and present danger to America'|date=September 12, 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> and senators [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Elizabeth Warren]], [[Cory Booker]], [[Kamala Harris]], and [[Chris Murphy (Connecticut politician)|Chris Murphy]]. They have interviewed several current and former [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 Democratic Presidential candidates]], including Sanders, Booker, Harris, [[Beto O'Rourke]], [[Andrew Yang]], [[Pete Buttigieg]], [[Marianne Williamson]], and [[Amy Klobuchar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/|title=Pod Save America Archives|website=Crooked Media|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>. Guests are often referred to as \"friends of the pod\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/en_ca/article/a3jadk/podcasts-are-becoming-the-lefts-right-wing-talk-radio|title=Podcasts are becoming the left's right-wing talk radio|work=VICE News|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pod Save America (30363).jpg|thumb|Favreau, Vietor, and guest [[Seth Meyers]] at a live taping at [[Radio City Music Hall]]]]\n\n== Reception ==\nThe show averages more than 1.5 million listeners an episode, and had been downloaded more than 120 million times by November 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' described the podcast as \"one of the big breakout hits of the nascent resistance movement\",<ref name=\":1\" /> and \"the left's answer to conservative talk radio... with a shoestring budget and no organizational backing, its hosts seem to have created something that liberals have spent almost two decades, and hundreds of millions of dollars, futilely searching for\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called it \"one of the nation's most popular podcasts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Pod-Save-America-about-to-take-its-next-step-12418780.php|title='Pod Save America' about to take its next step|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> ''[[GQ]]'' called it one of the \"most popular strategies for coping with the looming death of the republic\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/pod-save-america-colbert|title=The 'Pod Save America' Guys Gave Donald Trump His Best, Weirdest Nickname Yet|last=Willis|first=Jay|date=April 6, 2017|work=GQ|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote that the show's hosts \"do something far more rare [than political analysis], which is to make politics entertaining and even fun, without ever downplaying what they see as the threat posed to American democracy by the man elected to defend it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/crooked-media-fights-trump-pod-save-america-jon-favreau-jon-lovett-tommy-570695|title=How the Crooked Media trio is taking on Donald Trump with \"Pod Save America\"|date=March 26, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=January 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pod Save the World]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://crooked.com/podcast-series/pod-save-america/}}\n\n{{Crooked Media}}\n\n[[Category:2017 podcast debuts]]\n[[Category:Audio podcasts]]\n[[Category:Political podcasts]]\n[[Category:Crooked Media]]\n", "name_user": "71.82.77.112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pod_Save_America"}
{"title_page": "Just Mercy", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Destin Daniel Cretton}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Just Mercy\n| image          = Just Mercy Official Poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Destin Daniel Cretton]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Gil Netter\n* Asher Goldstein\n* [[Michael B. Jordan]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Destin Daniel Cretton\n* Andrew Lanham\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''Just Mercy: A Story of Justice and Redemption'' (2014)|[[Bryan Stevenson]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Michael B. Jordan\n* [[Jamie Foxx]]\n* [[Rob Morgan (actor)|Rob Morgan]]\n* [[Tim Blake Nelson]]\n* [[Rafe Spall]]\n* [[Brie Larson]]\n}}\n| music          = Joel P. West\n| cinematography = Brett Pawlak\n| editing        = [[Nat Sanders]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Endeavor Content\n* One Community\n* [[Participant Media]]\n* Macro Media\n* Gil Netter Productions\n* Outlier Society\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|9|6|[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2019|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 136 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiff.net/events/just-mercy|title=Just Mercy|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=July 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143720/https://tiff.net/events/just-mercy|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $25 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Just-Mercy#tab=summary |title=Just Mercy (2019) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225040102/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Just-Mercy#tab=summary |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/just-mercy-tells-story-walter-mcmillian-wrongfully-convicted-man-who-n1070431 |title= Just Mercy\" tells the story of Walter McMillian, a wrongfully convicted man who fights a flawed criminal justice system |date=October 24, 2019|website=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 5, 2020 }}</ref>\n| gross          = $50.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl419792385/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |title=Just Mercy (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108213403/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl419792385/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |archive-date=January 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Just Mercy''''' is a 2019 American [[legal drama]] film directed by [[Destin Daniel Cretton]], and starring [[Michael B. Jordan]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Rob Morgan (actor)|Rob Morgan]], [[Tim Blake Nelson]], [[Rafe Spall]], and [[Brie Larson]]. It tells the true story of [[Walter McMillian]], who, with the help of young defense attorney [[Bryan Stevenson]], appeals his murder conviction. The film is based on the memoir of the same name, written by Stevenson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://justmercy.eji.org |title=Just Mercy by Bryan Stevenson {{!}} Bestselling Book and Adapted Film |website=JustMercy.eji.org |language=en-US |access-date=2019-11-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120183622/https://justmercy.eji.org/ |archive-date=November 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Just Mercy'' had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 6, 2019, and was theatrically released by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] on December 25, 2019. The film received positive reviews from critics, and Foxx received a nomination for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role]] at the [[26th Screen Actors Guild Awards]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1989, idealistic young [[Harvard Law School|Harvard law]] graduate [[Bryan Stevenson]] travels to [[Alabama]] hoping to help fight for poor people who cannot afford proper legal representation. He meets with Eva Ansley and founds the [[Equal Justice Initiative]], then travels to a prison to meet its [[death row]] inmates. He meets [[Walter McMillian|Walter \"Johnny D.\" McMillian]], an African-American man who was convicted of the 1986 murder of Ronda Morrison, a white woman. Stevenson looks over the evidence in the case and discovers it hinges entirely on the testimony of convicted felon Ralph Myers, who provided highly self-contradictory testimony in exchange for a lighter sentence in his own pending trial.\n\nStevenson's first move is to ask prosecutor Tommy Chapman for aid; Chapman dismisses him without even looking at Stevenson's notes. Stevenson then asks McMillian family friend Darnell Houston to testify that he was with a witness who corroborated Myers' testimony the day of the murder, which would cause the prosecution's case to fall apart. When Stevenson submits Houston's testimony, police arrest him for perjury. While Stevenson is able to get the perjury charges dismissed, Houston is intimidated into refusing to testify in court.\n\nStevenson then approaches Myers himself, who eventually admits that his testimony was coerced after police played to his fear of being burned and threatened to have him executed by electric chair. Stevenson appeals to the local court to grant McMillan a retrial and successfully convinces Myers to recant his testimony on the stand, but the judge nevertheless refuses to grant a retrial. Distraught, Stevenson vents his frustrations about the case to Ansley. He appears on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' to rally public support in favor of McMillan, then appeals to the [[Supreme Court of Alabama]]. The Supreme Court overturns the circuit court's decision, and grants McMillan his retrial. Stevenson then motions to have the charges dismissed entirely. He confronts Chapman at his home and tries to convince him to join him in his motion; Chapman angrily ejects him from his property. The day of the motion comes, and Stevenson appeals to the judge. Chapman agrees to join him in his motion, the case is dismissed, and McMillan is finally reunited with his family.\n\nAn epilogue notes that Stevenson and Ansley continue to fight for justice to the present day. Until his death in 2013, McMillan remained friends with Stevenson. A follow-up investigation into Morrison's death confirmed McMillan's innocence and posited that a white man was likely responsible; the case has never been solved.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Michael B. Jordan]] as [[Bryan Stevenson]]\n* [[Jamie Foxx]] as [[Walter McMillian]]\n* [[Brie Larson]] as Eva Ansley\n* [[Rob Morgan (actor)|Rob Morgan]] as Herbert Richardson\n* [[Tim Blake Nelson]] as Ralph Myers\n* [[Rafe Spall]] as Tommy Chapman\n* [[O'Shea Jackson Jr.]] as [[Anthony Ray Hinton]]\n* [[Darrell Britt-Gibson]] as Darnell Houston\n* Lindsay Ayliffe as Judge Foster\n* C.J. LeBlanc as John McMillan\n* [[Ron Clinton Smith]] as Woodrow Ikner\n* Dominic Bogart as Doug Ansley\n* Hayes Mercure as Jeremy\n* Karan Kendrick as Minnie McMillian\n* [[Kirk Bovill]] as David Walker\n* Terence Rosemore as Jimmy\n}}\n\n==Production==\nDevelopment on the film began in 2015, when [[Broad Green Pictures]] hired [[Destin Daniel Cretton]] to direct, with [[Michael B. Jordan]] set to star.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/walk-in-the-woods-boosts-broad-green-pictures-1201587766/|title='Walk in the Woods' Boosts Broad Green Pictures|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|date=8 September 2015|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2019-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143718/https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/walk-in-the-woods-boosts-broad-green-pictures-1201587766/|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2017, [[Warner Bros.]] acquired the distribution rights for the film, after Broad Green Pictures had entered bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-bros-picks-up-michael-b-jordan-legal-drama-just-mercy-1063288|title=Warner Bros. Picks Up Michael B. Jordan Legal Drama 'Just Mercy'|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=November 30, 2017|access-date=August 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716190757/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-bros-picks-up-michael-b-jordan-legal-drama-just-mercy-1063288|archive-date=July 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, [[Jamie Foxx]] was set to co-star,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jamie-foxx-join-michael-b-jordan-legal-drama-just-mercy-1121148|title=Jamie Foxx in Talks to Join Michael B. Jordan in Legal Drama 'Just Mercy'|first=Borys|last=Kit|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 13, 2018|access-date=August 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143719/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jamie-foxx-join-michael-b-jordan-legal-drama-just-mercy-1121148|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and in August 2018, [[Brie Larson]], [[O'Shea Jackson Jr.]] and [[Tim Blake Nelson]] also joined the cast, with filming starting in [[Montgomery, Alabama]], by August 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brie-larson-joins-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1133417|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|title=Brie Larson Joins Michael B. Jordan in 'Just Mercy'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 8, 2018|access-date=August 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143715/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brie-larson-joins-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1133417|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oshea-jackson-jr-joins-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1135692|title=O'Shea Jackson Jr. Joins Michael B. Jordan in 'Just Mercy' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|date=August 17, 2018|access-date=August 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143713/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oshea-jackson-jr-joins-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1135692|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/just-mercy-michael-b-jordan-tim-blake-nelson-1202917880/|title=Michael B. Jordan's 'Just Mercy' Adds Tim Blake Nelson (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|website=Variety|date=27 August 2018|publisher=|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801092236/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/just-mercy-michael-b-jordan-tim-blake-nelson-1202917880/|archive-date=August 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eji.org/news/just-mercy-movie-films-in-montgomery|title=\"Just Mercy\" Movie Films in Montgomery|website=Equal Justice Initiative|date=August 30, 2018|access-date=August 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723143722/https://eji.org/news/just-mercy-movie-films-in-montgomery|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2018, actors Dominic Bogart, Hayes Mercure and Karan Kendrick were added as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/snls-beck-bennett-darcy-carden-greener-grass-just-mercy-dominic-bogart-hayes-mercure-1202474313/|title='SNL's Beck Bennett, D'Arcy Carden Star In 'Greener Grass'; 'Just Mercy' Adds Dominic Bogart & Hayes Mercure|first1=Amanda|last1=N'Duka|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=1 October 2018|publisher=|access-date=October 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418204537/https://deadline.com/2018/10/snls-beck-bennett-darcy-carden-greener-grass-just-mercy-dominic-bogart-hayes-mercure-1202474313/|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/karan-kendrick-just-mercy-doctor-sleep-jocelin-donahue-1202474899/|title=Karan Kendrick Cast In 'Just Mercy'; 'Doctor Sleep' Adds Jocelin Donahue|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=October 2, 2018|accessdate=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822040607/https://deadline.com/2018/10/karan-kendrick-just-mercy-doctor-sleep-jocelin-donahue-1202474899/|archive-date=August 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker,' 'Ford v Ferrari,' 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres|website=Variety|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=July 23, 2019|accessdate=July 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140739/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It received an awards qualifying limited release on December 25, 2019.<ref>McClintock, Pamela (July 16, 2019), [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-b-jordans-just-mercy-lands-year-end-awards-release-sesame-street-officially-pushed-1224638 \"Michael B. Jordan's 'Just Mercy' Lands Year-End Awards Release; 'Sesame Street' Officially Pushed\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716190754/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-b-jordans-just-mercy-lands-year-end-awards-release-sesame-street-officially-pushed-1224638 |date=July 16, 2019 }}, ''The Hollywood Reporter''.</ref> Originally set to expand to a wide release on January 17, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/warner-bros-melissa-mccarthy-comedy-superintelligence-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1202373177/|title=Warner Bros Dates Melissa McCarthy Comedy 'Superintelligence' & Michael B. Jordan's 'Just Mercy'|first1=Amanda|last1=N'Duka|date=20 April 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=2019-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330021041/https://deadline.com/2018/04/warner-bros-melissa-mccarthy-comedy-superintelligence-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-1202373177/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the film's expansion was moved up to January 10, 2020, when it opened in 2,375 theaters.<ref>[https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl419792385/?ref_=bo_hm_RECENT_WEEKEND_WIDGET_5 \"Just Mercy\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117175859/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl419792385/?ref_=bo_hm_RECENT_WEEKEND_WIDGET_5 |date=January 17, 2020 }}, Box Office Mojo.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Just-Mercy#tab=box-office |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225040102/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Just-Mercy#tab=box-office |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nOn its first day of limited release the film made $81,072 from four theaters.<ref name=THRlimited>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rise-skywalker-unwraps-huge-35m-christmas-little-women-opens-1264949|title=Box Office: 'Star Wars: Rise of Skywalker' Unwraps Huge $32M on Christmas Day|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 25, 2019|accessdate=December 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226084855/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rise-skywalker-unwraps-huge-35m-christmas-little-women-opens-1264949|archive-date=December 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It went on to make $105,000 in its opening weekend (a five-day total of $228,072).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/clemency-neon-just-mercy-warner-bros-1917-universal-specialty-box-office-1202818143/ |title=\u20181917\u2019, \u2018Just Mercy\u2019 And \u2018Clemency\u2019 Open Strong In Limited Debuts Over Busy Holiday Weekend \u2013 Specialty Box Office |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=December 29, 2019 |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229231925/https://deadline.com/2019/12/clemency-neon-just-mercy-warner-bros-1917-universal-specialty-box-office-1202818143/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film made $425,862 over its 15 days of limited release. It then made $3.7 million on its first day of wide release, including $800,000 from Thursday-night previews. The film went on to make $10 million over the weekend, finishing fourth.<ref name=WideOpening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/box-office-1917-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-like-a-boss-1202826743/ |title=\u20181917\u2019 Strong With $36M+, But \u2018Like A Boss\u2019 & \u2018Just Mercy\u2019 Fighting Over 4th With $10M; Why Kristen Stewart\u2019s \u2018Underwater\u2019 Went Kerplunk With $6M+ |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 12, 2020 |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112062751/https://deadline.com/2020/01/box-office-1917-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-like-a-boss-1202826743/ |archive-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film made $5.8 million in its second weekend of wide release (and $7.5 million over the four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]] holiday), finishing seventh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-1917-weekend-box-office-1202833726/|title=\u2018Bad Boys For Life\u2019 So Great With $100M+ Worldwide; \u2018Dolittle\u2019 Still A Dud With $57M+ Global \u2013 Box Office Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=January 20, 2020|date=January 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120213703/https://deadline.com/2020/01/bad-boys-for-life-dolittle-1917-weekend-box-office-1202833726/|archive-date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 83% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 269 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 6.98/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"''Just Mercy'' dramatizes a real-life injustice with solid performances, a steady directorial hand, and enough urgency to overcome a certain degree of earnest advocacy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/just_mercy |title=Just Mercy (2019) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114051829/https://rottentomatoes.com/m/just_mercy |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 68 out of 100 based on 49 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/just-mercy |title=Just Mercy Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115161508/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/just-mercy |archive-date=January 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a rare average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received an average 4.5 out of 5 stars, with 73% of people saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=WideOpening/>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[AARP#AARP Awards|AARP's Movies For Grownups Awards]]\n| January 11, 2020\n| Best Supporting Actor\n|rowspan=2| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|